# Design System Rules

**Figma Token Matching**
Always use the same tokens as defined in Figma. Do not hardcode values.

**Sentence case**
Use sentence case for UI copy (headings, labels, buttons, messages, placeholders): capitalize only the first word and proper nouns. Do not use title case (capitalizing every major word).

```tsx
// Good
"Default model"
"Reset to default"
"Per-feature overrides"
"Agents (under Agent Studio)"

// Bad
"Default Model"
"Per-Feature Overrides"
"Product Areas"
```

**Semantic Tokens First**
Prefer semantic tokens over raw palette values:
- Text: `text.primary`, `text.secondary`, `text.disabled`
- States: `action.hover`, `action.selected`, `action.disabled`
- Surfaces: `background.default`, `background.paper`, `divider`

```tsx
// Good
color: theme.palette.text.secondary

// Bad
color: theme.palette.grey[600]
```

**Typography**
Use MUI `<Typography>` with `variant` matching the Figma text style. Avoid raw HTML text elements. Do not use `sx` prop to override typography styles (fontSize, fontWeight, fontFamily, lineHeight, etc.) — use `variant` instead.

Do not use font weight overrides (e.g. `sx={{ fontWeight: 600 }}`). Use the appropriate Typography variant that carries the desired weight (e.g. `subtitle1`, `subtitle2`, `h3`).

```tsx
// Good
<Typography variant="body1">Text</Typography>
<Typography variant="h2">Heading</Typography>
<Typography variant="subtitle2">Label</Typography>

// Bad
<p>Text</p>
<Typography sx={{ fontSize: "16px", fontWeight: 600 }}>Text</Typography>
<Typography variant="body1" sx={{ fontWeight: 600 }}>Label</Typography>
```
